text: Interview with Michael Collins coming in 3, 2, 1. My guest today is Michael Collins, who was the command module pilot on Apollo 11, that historic flight 15 years ago when man first walked on the surface of the moon. Mr. Collins, when did you join the space program? I joined the space program in January of 1964, slightly over 20 years ago, although it doesn't seem that long. What was going on in the space program at the time, and why were you motivated to go into it? Well, I joined right after Mercury and before Gemini, and that was in the days when NASA was looking for test pilots to be astronauts, and I was a test pilot out at Edwards Air Force Base, California, and the idea of working for NASA and flying a little higher and a little faster was very appealing to me. What was it like then to be an astronaut? They were very busy and they were very exciting times. I was in the third group of astronauts. There first was a group of seven, then a group of nine, and then the third group of 14, making a total of 30 people. So we were small enough that we knew each other all very well, and we were working together very well as a team, and we were spending most of our time in the early days looking at the design of the Gemini and the design of the Apollo to make sure that they made sense from the pilot's point of view, the people who were going to be operating that very complicated equipment. We had more to do than there were hours in the day. It was very busy. We were doing a lot of traveling. It was a very interesting and exciting time. You flew on one of the Gemini missions, right? Could you describe that? Yes, I flew with John Young on Gemini 10 in July of 1966, and it was a three-day flight designed primarily to check out the practicality of various rendezvous procedures. We had an Agena launched a couple of hours before us, and we took off from Cape Kennedy and found the Agena in the sky and rendezvoused and docked with it, and then we used its power, its engine, to boost us up into a higher orbit where we found a second Agena, one that had been up there for several months and was electrically dead, an inert Agena, and we made a rendezvous with it using entirely optical techniques. In other words, it didn't have any capability of responding to our radar, so we made two rendezvous, one using radar with our own Agena and one without radar on this inert Agena, and then I made a spacewalk over to the second Agena and retrieved from it a scientific package, which we returned to the Gemini and then subsequently back to Earth. It was a very, very busy flight. We really had more to do in three days than we could shoehorn in, and it was very exciting. How do you compare spacewalking then to spacewalking now? For example, the spacewalks that were conducted by Bruce McCandless and Pinky Nelson in previous space shuttle missions when they used the man-maneuvering units. Well, our equipment was not nearly as fancy or good or complicated as the equipment they have now. We didn't know as many things. For example, instead of that gigantic backpack, which McCandless wore, I had a small handheld gun-like device which squirted out little jets of cold gas. The difference is I had to point it in precisely the right direction or I would miss my target or I would start, if I didn't hold it in proper alignment with my body, I would start tumbling in the McCandless equipment. There are gyroscopes and automatic devices to prevent those things. So ours was very crude and rudimentary compared to the equipment they have now. Of course, ours was also a lot smaller, which it had to be on the Gemini because it itself was a very small machine. Would you like to spacewalk now with all this new technology? Oh, I would. I'd love to, yes. I think that would be wonderful. The backpack is almost a miniature spacecraft itself and I think it would be a great deal of fun to motor scooter around the sky in the vicinity of the shuttle and I'd love to do that. Let's go back to the Gemini program. Well, the Gemini program was a very nice program. It's not well remembered today because it fell in the shadow of Apollo, but we really could not have had Apollo or Apollo could not have been as successful as it was had there not been a Gemini program. Gemini was required really to do three things. The first thing was to prove that rendezvous and docking in space was practical because the Apollo scheme required that the Apollo spaceship break itself into two pieces, one piece to land on the moon, the second piece to remain in lunar orbit. For this scheme to be successful, it was necessary that we have a safe and a practical rendezvous, a procedure for bringing these two pieces back together. The second was to prove that you could stay in space for long enough in weightlessness to make the trip from the earth to the moon and back again without any deleterious effect on the human body. And then the third thing was if you are going to go land on the moon, you have to operate outside on the surface independent of the vehicle itself. And Gemini was designed to give us some experience in extravehicular operations or spacewalking. Then those three things, rendezvous, long duration, and extravehicular activities were the main reasons for Gemini's being. And it did prove that all three of those things were practical. And it led then very logically into Apollo. After Gemini, you began working in the Apollo program and you became a specialist in the command module part of the Apollo equipment. What happened then? I was assigned to Apollo 11, the first lunar landing flight. It was preceded by Apollo 7, 8, 9, and 10. 7 was a flight in earth orbit to prove that the command module was airworthy. 8 took the command module all the way to the moon. 9 was back in earth orbit and introduced the lunar module along with the command module. 10 then took the lunar and command modules to the moon in a dress rehearsal. And then 11 was the first lunar landing flight. So you can see we moved fairly quickly. Once we got into Apollo, we didn't waste much time in landing. We just had four preliminary flights and we could not have moved that rapidly had we not built up a strong foundation of experience on the Gemini program. Apollo 11 was a very exciting flight. It was, although it was followed by a number of other flights in many of our minds, it was sort of the culmination or the apex or the apogee of the Apollo program because President Kennedy had said that before the end of the decade, we were to land a man on the moon and return him safely to earth. And on Apollo 11, we did that even double. We landed two men on the moon and returned them safely to earth. So we felt that we were fulfilling the presidential mandate and there was great attention and pressure brought to bear on us as the crew of Apollo 11. What was the historical value of Apollo 11? One effect, I think, of the first lunar landing was to bring people of all nations closer together. For example, after the flight of Apollo 11, we three crew members took a very quick trip around the world. We visited, if I recall correctly, some 22 countries in slightly over a month's time. And we noticed that everywhere we went, no matter what the country, no matter what its politics, the people there seemed to identify very closely with us and with the Apollo program. They felt indeed a part of it. They felt part of humankind's first step out onto the surface of another planet. And I think that flight of Apollo 11 did make the world a little bit smaller and a little bit friendlier and did give it a feeling of unity that had not existed before. Do you think it was worthwhile going to the moon? Yes, I definitely think going to the moon was worth it. It's difficult to put numbers on things. The Apollo program costs around $24 billion, which is a huge amount of money. There have been studies run which suggest that for every dollar you spend in the space program, there is a fallout or a spin-off of several dollars of beneficial effects throughout our economy. People trace miniaturization, advances in electronics, the use of exotic new materials, and a host of allied advances to the space program. I feel that the space program is paying for itself, and I feel that the lunar landing was especially useful because I feel, I believe, that eventually we're going to leave this planet and we're going to go out through the universe, and we're going to have, in the long run, a choice of either living here or living somewhere else. And if you believe that, then you have to get started on that venture somewhere along the line, and taking that small step from Earth to Moon is a necessary part of that to be followed by a little bit longer step to Mars and then perhaps to Titan, one of the satellites of Saturn, and on we go from there. Do you think we ought to go back to the Moon? I think there will be good reasons for going back to the Moon, and in time astronomers would love to go to the Moon. If they could get over on the backside of the Moon, they wouldn't have any interference from all the electromagnetic noise that we make here on Earth, and any information they received from the stars would be pure, unfiltered information. and they'd love to put up a transparent dome on the far side of the Moon and quietly listen to what the universe is trying to tell us. In similar fashion, people would like to mine the Moon. It's very rich in heavy elements such as titanium. Others would like to use those lunar materials to create a miniature planet, a gigantic space station somewhere between the Earth and the Moon. Personally, if I were designing a program of exploration, I would rather go learn a little bit more about Mars before I would return to the Moon. In fact, in your book, Carrying the Fire, you mentioned something about hoping man would visit Mars in your lifetime, and you call that magic. So you still feel that way? Personally, I think there's a lot more to be learned by human beings prowling around the surface of Mars. One Viking landing is like aliens sending one probe to Earth, and it lands in the middle of the Mojave Desert, and therefore those people think they know all there is to know about Earth. They think it's homogeneously like the Mojave Desert. So I think there's a lot to be learned by prowling around other regions on Mars and developing the capability for people to fly off on a long voyage. Mars would be about close to a two-year trip. It's a, you know, that's right. It's about nine months minimum one way, and then if you want to spend any time there, the first thing you know is you've almost used up two years. I've always thought I wanted to go to Mars. From the time I was a little kid, I wanted to go to Mars. I was never that interested in the Moon, but I always wanted to go to Mars. And then you ended up going to the Moon instead. Yes, I got the wrong planet. Ended up with the Moon instead of Mars. What do you think of the progress made in the space program today? Do you think we're going in the right direction? I think the shuttle is a wonderful machine. The design of the shuttle is an excellent one, and it's performing magnificently, and I think it leads logically into a permanent station in Earth orbit. So you are in favor of building the manned space station? Oh, yes, yes. I think it's a necessary step, and I think it's one that will probably pay its own way. We're already discovering that there are certain advantages to weightlessness. We can purify pharmaceutical products. We can manufacture perfect spheres of different materials, and already we're discovering practical ways of using weightlessness. And I think when we get a station that's able to stay up in Earth orbit indefinitely, that those ways will multiply. Let's go back to Apollo 11. How did you get to the Moon? Could you describe that? When it's about a quarter of a million miles away, and it takes about three days to get there, you leave Cape Kennedy and northeastern Florida, and in 10 or 11 minutes you find yourself in orbit around the Earth. You stay in orbit around the Earth for a couple of hours to make sure that all your equipment is functioning properly, and then you reignite your rocket engine, and you speed up to around 25,000 miles an hour, which is the speed required to break the bond of Earth's gravity. That then puts you on a trajectory which you hope will cause you barely to miss the Moon, some three days later. And during those three days you're navigating, you're talking to people back on Earth who have very powerful radar sets, and you make sure that you're going right down the center line of that imaginary highway, and if you're not you make some small corrections with your rocket engine to stay on the proper course. Then when you arrive at the Moon, you just miss it a little bit. You go right ahead of it by about 60 miles, and as you skim by it, you ignite your engine again and you slow down so that the Earth's or the Moon's gravity is now able to capture you, and after a little correction or two, you find yourself in a circular orbit about 60 miles above the surface of the Moon. You spend a day there and make sure everything is working right, and then the lunar module separates from the command module, and the lunar module with two people on board, in this case Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin, descend rather leisurely and break to a halt and land while you whiz by overhead. Then they proceed to explore the surface of the Moon for a couple of hours, get a little sleep, come on back, launch from the Moon, and find you as you go by overhead. Once the two of you are docked, the lunar module is jettisoned and allowed to remain in orbit, and then you use the command module engine to break the bond of lunar gravity, and again get yourself on a trajectory which will cause you to head back to Earth, and to just barely graze the atmosphere of the Earth, come coasting in at a shallow angle, and get captured by Earth's gravity, and as the friction of hitting the atmosphere increases, the spacecraft slows down, and eventually you open your parachutes and plop into the ocean some eight days after you began, and that's how you go to the Moon, and that's what we did on Apollo 11. What were your feelings when Armstrong was making that first step on the Moon, and what were you thinking about when you were there all alone in the command module with the Moon between you and everybody else? My concerns were really not for me and what was going on inside the command module, but I was concerned about what might happen to Armstrong and Aldrin on the surface of the Moon, and then even more than that, I was concerned about their ability to come back up in rendezvous and find me. The rendezvous procedure is a fairly complicated one when everything is working exactly right, and if things start breaking, if the radar doesn't work properly or something else happens, if they get off late, there are a number of variations on the theme which then ensue, and these can be extraordinarily complicated. So I was mostly concerned about rendezvous. When I heard that they were out on the surface, that made me really feel good. I had a feeling of shared pride, just as the people here on Earth did, that everything seemed to be going very successfully, but I still in the back of my mind had a nagging fear about the rendezvous and the docking. As far as my being alone, as I said before, I rather enjoyed that, and I didn't have any concerns about that. It was a fun feeling to be over on the backside of the Moon all by myself, knowing I was the only human in that part of the universe. Over on the other side there were three billion plus two, three billion on that funny little blue blob that I could see when I swung around onto the front side, and then two down below me. But when I was over on the rear of the Moon, I had the whole universe to myself, and I rather enjoyed that feeling. This concludes our interview for today with Michael Collins, Command Module Pilot on Apollo 11.
